{"title_page": "Duncan McNair", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n'''Duncan William McNair''',  [[Order of the Holy Sepulchre|KHS]] is a commercial and corporate litigation lawyer and author, the youngest of seven children of [[Robin McNair|Squadron Leader Robin McNair]], [[Distinguished Flying Cross (United Kingdom)|DFC]] and [[Medal bar|Bar]], and his wife, Estelle (n\u00e9e Townsend), who was a great-niece of Surgeon-General Sir [[Edmond Townsend]] [[Order of the Bath|KCB]] [[Order of St Michael and St George|CMG]].\n\n==Life and career==\nMcNair was educated as a State Scholar at [[St Benedict's School, Ealing|St Benedict's School]], Ealing and at the [[University of Bristol]], where he was Vice-President of the University Debating Union. He has practised City oriented litigation at Lovells (now [[Hogan Lovells]]), at [[Lawrence Graham|Lawrence Graham LLP]], and, since 2012, at Cubism Law,<ref name=\"Cubism Lawyer profile\">{{cite web |title=Duncan McNair - Commercial Litigators London, UK - Cubism Law |url=http://www.cubismlaw.com/our-lawyers/duncan-mcnair/}}</ref> specialising in major commercial and corporate litigation and public law cases, domestically and internationally.<ref name=\"Telegraph Article\">{{cite news|last=Blackmore|first=Nicole|title=My Cyprus mortgage payments went up by 166%|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/personalfinance/borrowing/mortgages/10516732/My-Cyprus-mortgage-repayments-went-up-by-166pc.html|accessdate=31 March 2014|newspaper=The Telegraph|date=15 December 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Protection of Life During Pregnancy Bill===\nIn 2011 McNair acted for the successful third party interveners in [[A, B and C v Ireland|A, B & C \u2013v- Republic of Ireland]], before the Grand Chamber of the [[European Court of Human Rights]] (ECHR).<ref>{{cite web|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110108215651/http://www.lawgazette.co.uk/news/lawyer-in-the-news/duncan-mcnair-acted-pro-life-campaigners-over-right-abortion|archivedate=8 January 2011|url=http://www.lawgazette.co.uk/news/lawyer-in-the-news/duncan-mcnair-acted-pro-life-campaigners-over-right-abortion|title=Duncan McNair acted for pro-life campaigners over right to abortion|work=Law Society Gazette|author=Jonathan Rayner|date=6 January 2011|accessdate=28 August 2013}}</ref> This was a landmark case in which the court dismissed a wide range of complaints by A, B and C, claiming lack of access to abortion facilities in Ireland. The court upheld only one complaint brought by the Claimants as to breach by Ireland of Article 8 ECHR (Right to Privacy). In light of the ABC case, the Irish Government introduced<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-23507923 the Protection of Life During Pregnancy Bill]</ref> the Protection of Life During Pregnancy Bill to detail the circumstances under which abortions in Ireland could be legally performed. This passed into law in July 2013.<ref>[http://www.thejournal.ie/president-signs-protection-of-life-during-pregnancy-bill-into-law-1014930-Jul2013 ''Protection of Life During Pregnancy Bill'' passes into law in July 2013].</ref>\n\n===Other notable cases===\nIn 2012 he acted for successful interveners in [[BPAS]] \u2013v- Secretary of State for Health, in the [[Administrative Court (England and Wales)|Administrative Court]] in London.\n\nHe was named respectively both \"Lawyer in the News\" (Law Society Gazette) and \"Lawyer of the Week\" (The Times) for his conduct of these cases.<ref>\"Lawyer of the Week Duncan McNair\". The Times. London. 24 February 2011. Retrieved 7 October 2013.</ref>\n\nIn 2015 he led a large team of lawyers in an abuse of dominant position action against Rolls-Royce.\n\n===The McNair Inquiry and Report===\n\nIn 2012 McNair was appointed by the [[RSPCA]] to chair a national review of its Freedom Food scheme.<ref>[http://www.freedomfood.co.uk/aboutus Freedom Food scheme]</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.farminguk.com/content/DigitalIssue/93/#30|title=RSPCA urged to maintain and increase support for Freedom Food Assurance Scheme \u2013 Interview with Duncan McNair|location=Yorkshire|date=September 2013|accessdate=17 September 2013}}</ref> Serving on his panel were former Cabinet minister and Secretary of State at [[DEFRA]], the Rt Hon (now Dame) [[Caroline Spelman]] (MP), and Prof. [http://www.bris.ac.uk/vetscience/people/david-c-main/index.html David Main] (BVetMed, PhD, MRCVS), Reader in Animal Welfare and Behaviour at the University of Bristol Veterinary School. Evidence was taken from all areas of animal food production, distribution and retail and from interested parties.<ref>[http://www.rspca.org.uk/ImageLocator/LocateAsset?asset=document&assetId=1232733303590&mode=stg ''The McNair Report'' website]</ref> ''The McNair Report'' was presented in May 2013. Its recommendations were unanimously approved by the Council of Trustees of the RSPCA the following month. The RSPCA later announced it was formulating a strategy to build on the recommendations of the ''McNair Report'' <ref>{{cite web|last=McNair|first=Duncan|title=Independent review of Freedom Food|url=http://www.freedomfood.co.uk/review|publisher=RSPCA|accessdate=31 March 2014}}</ref> which formed the basis of their RSPCA Assured scheme. The scheme is dedicated to the better welfare of hundreds of millions of farmed animals across the UK and is influential upon schemes affecting many billion farmed animals across the world.\n\n=== Charity work ===\nMcNair undertakes extensive pro bono charity work, especially in the field of local communities and animal welfare. In 2015 he founded Save The Asian Elephants (\"[https://stae.org/ STAE]\"), a coalition of politicians, academics, lawyers, field experts and campaigners working to protect the Asian elephant from abuse and extinction ([https://stae.org www.stae.org]).  He has addressed many influential audiences on the issues arising and solutions formulated by STAE in liaison with specialists in India, the UK, and worldwide.\n\nMcNair also speaks and publishes widely on issues relating to animal welfare in the context of food production, distribution and retail and problems associated with livestock supply chains.\n\nMcNair is active in various initiatives to help local communities and schools.\n\n=== Attributions ===\nMcNair is described in his legal profession work as \"''indefatigable''\" and is named as \"''the client's champion''\" in the 2015 edition of Legal 500, a leading client and peer review of recommended UK lawyers.\n\n==Honours and Awards==\nDuncan McNair was appointed a [[Order of the Holy Sepulchre|Knight of the Holy Sepulchre]] (KHS) by the Roman Catholic Church in 2002. {{citation needed|date=October 2013}}\n\nMcNair was named Winner of the \"Animal Hero of the Year\" competition at the [https://www.animalstarawards.com/winners-2018/ Animal Star Awards 2018], an event attracting 850 nominations across the UK.\n\n==Books==\nMcNair has written two books, ''The Morello Letters \u2013 Pen pal to the stars''<ref>''The Morello Letters \u2013 Pen pal to the stars'', Harper Collins, 2006; {{ISBN|978-0007241231}}</ref> and ''More Morello Letters \u2013 Pen pal to the superstars''<ref>''More Morello Letters \u2013 Pen pal to the superstars'', Harper Collins, 2011; {{ISBN|978-0956342225}}</ref> under the pseudonym of a fictional Italian immigrant, \"Mrs Morello, a lover of all things British\", who struggles to understand some of the more idiosyncratic aspects of British life. Both books have been widely reviewed and acclaimed.<ref>\"Banana Trouble\" [book review], ''[[Accountancy Age]]'', 19 October 2006. ''[[Business Source Complete]]''; last accessed 29 August 2013</ref><ref>\"The King of the spoofs\" [book review], ''The Evening Post'' (Nottinghamshire), 9 September 2006: pg. 18, ''[[Newspaper Source Plus]]''; last accessed 29 August 2013.</ref><ref>\"Bishop and Lord Mayor 'booked'\" [book review]. ''Coventry Evening Telegraph'' (England), 16 December 2006: 2. ''[[InfoTrac]]''; last accessed 29 August 2013</ref> In 2012 The Morello Letters was included by [[BBC Radio 4]] listeners amongst their funniest books ever in Open Book\u2019s Listeners\u2019 Funniest Books hosted by [[Mariella Frostrup]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b01946wg |title=BBC Radio 4 - Open Book, Open Book Listeners' Funniest Books |publisher=Bbc.co.uk |date=2012-01-12 |accessdate=2017-02-18}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20130511013248/http://www.morelloworld.com/about-author.htm Morelloworld], book website\n*[http://www.freedomfood.co.uk/industry/industrynews/2013/02/independent-review-of-freedom-food RSPCA announces review of Freedom Food Scheme]\n*[http://www.rspca.org.uk/ImageLocator/LocateAsset?asset=document&assetId=1232733303590&mode=stg ''The McNair Report'']\n*[http://www.rspca.org.uk/freedomfood RSPCA Freedom Food farmed animal welfare assurance scheme]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:McNair, Duncan}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:English lawyers]]\n[[Category:English non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:English humorists]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Bristol]]\n[[Category:People educated at St Benedict's School]]\n[[Category:English Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:English male non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Knights of the Holy Sepulchre]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:People associated with Hogan Lovells]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n'''Duncan William McNair''',  [[Order of the Holy Sepulchre|KHS]] is a commercial and corporate litigation lawyer and author, the youngest of seven children of [[Robin McNair|Squadron Leader Robin McNair]], [[Distinguished Flying Cross (United Kingdom)|DFC]] and [[Medal bar|Bar]], and his wife, Estelle (n\u00e9e Townsend), who was a great-niece of Surgeon-General Sir [[Edmond Townsend]] [[Order of the Bath|KCB]] [[Order of St Michael and St George|CMG]].\n\n==Life and career==\nMcNair was educated as a State Scholar at [[St Benedict's School, Ealing|St Benedict's School]], Ealing and at the [[University of Bristol]], where he was Vice-President of the University Debating Union. He has practised City oriented litigation at Lovells (now [[Hogan Lovells]]), at [[Lawrence Graham|Lawrence Graham LLP]], and, since 2012, at Cubism Law,<ref name=\"Cubism Lawyer profile\">{{cite web |title=Duncan McNair - Commercial Litigators London, UK - Cubism Law |url=http://www.cubismlaw.com/our-lawyers/duncan-mcnair/}}</ref> specialising in major commercial and corporate litigation and public law cases, domestically and internationally.<ref name=\"Telegraph Article\">{{cite news|last=Blackmore|first=Nicole|title=My Cyprus mortgage payments went up by 166%|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/personalfinance/borrowing/mortgages/10516732/My-Cyprus-mortgage-repayments-went-up-by-166pc.html|accessdate=31 March 2014|newspaper=The Telegraph|date=15 December 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Protection of Life During Pregnancy Bill===\nIn 2011 McNair acted for the successful third party interveners in [[A, B and C v Ireland|A, B & C \u2013v- Republic of Ireland]], before the Grand Chamber of the [[European Court of Human Rights]] (ECHR).<ref>{{cite web|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110108215651/http://www.lawgazette.co.uk/news/lawyer-in-the-news/duncan-mcnair-acted-pro-life-campaigners-over-right-abortion|archivedate=8 January 2011|url=http://www.lawgazette.co.uk/news/lawyer-in-the-news/duncan-mcnair-acted-pro-life-campaigners-over-right-abortion|title=Duncan McNair acted for pro-life campaigners over right to abortion|work=Law Society Gazette|author=Jonathan Rayner|date=6 January 2011|accessdate=28 August 2013}}</ref> This was a landmark case in which the court dismissed a wide range of complaints by A, B and C, claiming lack of access to abortion facilities in Ireland. The court upheld only one complaint brought by the Claimants as to breach by Ireland of Article 8 ECHR (Right to Privacy). In light of the ABC case, the Irish Government introduced<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-23507923 the Protection of Life During Pregnancy Bill]</ref> the Protection of Life During Pregnancy Bill to detail the circumstances under which abortions in Ireland could be legally performed. This passed into law in July 2013.<ref>[http://www.thejournal.ie/president-signs-protection-of-life-during-pregnancy-bill-into-law-1014930-Jul2013 ''Protection of Life During Pregnancy Bill'' passes into law in July 2013].</ref>\n\n===Other notable cases===\nIn 2012 he acted for successful interveners in [[BPAS]] \u2013v- Secretary of State for Health, in the [[Administrative Court (England and Wales)|Administrative Court]] in London.\n\nHe was named respectively both \"Lawyer in the News\" (Law Society Gazette) and \"Lawyer of the Week\" (The Times) for his conduct of these cases.<ref>\"Lawyer of the Week Duncan McNair\". The Times. London. 24 February 2011. Retrieved 7 October 2013.</ref>\n\nIn 2015 he led a large team of lawyers in an abuse of dominant position action against Rolls-Royce.\n\n===The McNair Inquiry and Report===\n\nIn 2012 McNair was appointed by the [[RSPCA]] to chair a national review of its Freedom Food scheme.<ref>[http://www.freedomfood.co.uk/aboutus Freedom Food scheme]</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.farminguk.com/content/DigitalIssue/93/#30|title=RSPCA urged to maintain and increase support for Freedom Food Assurance Scheme \u2013 Interview with Duncan McNair|location=Yorkshire|date=September 2013|accessdate=17 September 2013}}</ref> Serving on his panel were former Cabinet minister and Secretary of State at [[DEFRA]], the Rt Hon (now Dame) [[Caroline Spelman]] (MP), and Prof. [http://www.bris.ac.uk/vetscience/people/david-c-main/index.html David Main] (BVetMed, PhD, MRCVS), Reader in Animal Welfare and Behaviour at the University of Bristol Veterinary School. Evidence was taken from all areas of animal food production, distribution and retail and from interested parties.<ref>[http://www.rspca.org.uk/ImageLocator/LocateAsset?asset=document&assetId=1232733303590&mode=stg ''The McNair Report'' website]</ref> ''The McNair Report'' was presented in May 2013. Its recommendations were unanimously approved by the Council of Trustees of the RSPCA the following month. The RSPCA later announced it was formulating a strategy to build on the recommendations of the ''McNair Report'' <ref>{{cite web|last=McNair|first=Duncan|title=Independent review of Freedom Food|url=http://www.freedomfood.co.uk/review|publisher=RSPCA|accessdate=31 March 2014}}</ref> which formed the basis of their RSPCA Assured scheme. The scheme is dedicated to the better welfare of hundreds of millions of farmed animals across the UK and is influential upon schemes affecting many billion farmed animals across the world.\n\n=== Charity work ===\nMcNair undertakes extensive pro bono charity work, especially in the field of local communities and animal welfare. In 2015 he founded Save The Asian Elephants (\"[https://stae.org/ STAE]\"), a coalition of politicians, academics, lawyers, field experts and campaigners working to protect the Asian elephant from abuse and extinction ([https://stae.org www.stae.org]).  He has addressed many influential audiences on the issues arising and solutions formulated by STAE in liaison with specialists in India, the UK, and worldwide.\n\nMcNair also speaks and publishes widely on issues relating to animal welfare in the context of food production, distribution and retail and problems associated with livestock supply chains.\n\nMcNair is active in various initiatives to help local communities and schools.\n\n=== Attributions ===\nMcNair is described in his legal profession work as \"''indefatigable''\" and is named as \"''the client's champion''\" in the 2015 edition of Legal 500, a leading client and peer review of recommended UK lawyers.\n\n==Honours and Awards==\nDuncan McNair was appointed a [[Order of the Holy Sepulchre|Knight of the Holy Sepulchre]] (KHS) by the Roman Catholic Church in 2002. {{citation needed|date=October 2013}}\n\nMcNair was named Winner of the \"Animal Hero of the Year\" competition at the [https://www.animalstarawards.com/winners-2018/ Animal Star Awards 2018], an event attracting 850 nominations across the UK.\n\n==Books==\nMcNair has written two books, ''The Morello Letters \u2013 Pen pal to the stars''<ref>''The Morello Letters \u2013 Pen pal to the stars'', Harper Collins, 2006; {{ISBN|978-0007241231}}</ref> and ''More Morello Letters \u2013 Pen pal to the superstars''<ref>''More Morello Letters \u2013 Pen pal to the superstars'', Harper Collins, 2011; {{ISBN|978-0956342225}}</ref> under the pseudonym of a fictional Italian immigrant, \"Mrs Morello, a lover of all things British\", who struggles to understand some of the more idiosyncratic aspects of British life. Both books have been widely reviewed and acclaimed.<ref>\"Banana Trouble\" [book review], ''[[Accountancy Age]]'', 19 October 2006. ''[[Business Source Complete]]''; last accessed 29 August 2013</ref><ref>\"The King of the spoofs\" [book review], ''The Evening Post'' (Nottinghamshire), 9 September 2006: pg. 18, ''[[Newspaper Source Plus]]''; last accessed 29 August 2013.</ref><ref>\"Bishop and Lord Mayor 'booked'\" [book review]. ''Coventry Evening Telegraph'' (England), 16 December 2006: 2. ''[[InfoTrac]]''; last accessed 29 August 2013</ref> In 2012 The Morello Letters was included by [[BBC Radio 4]] listeners amongst their funniest books ever in Open Book\u2019s Listeners\u2019 Funniest Books hosted by [[Mariella Frostrup]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b01946wg |title=BBC Radio 4 - Open Book, Open Book Listeners' Funniest Books |publisher=Bbc.co.uk |date=2012-01-12 |accessdate=2017-02-18}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://we